I. Introduction¶

The objective of this data challenge is to build machine learning models to predict the conversion probability for each loan offer. The dataset provided is a sample of the offers that users have clicked on in the past including information on both the lead (e.g., the user's self-report credit rating, income, etc) and the offers that they clicked on (e.g., the loan amount offered, APR, etc).

The project will be described as follows:

  1. Data cleaning and exploratory data analysis
  2. Building machine learning models
  3. Further model improvement with autoencoder
  4. Conclusion

From the above profile report, there are total of 141915 observations and 21 variables. Not all the variables are needed for the model.

  1. The dataset has 1 duplicate row. The duplicated observation should be removed.
  2. offer_id, rate_table_id, click_id, lead_uuid, are unique ids, which doesn't provide too much information. They should be dropped for the model.
  3. lead_created_at, rate_table_created_at are also unique timestamps. They can be dropped.
  4. monthly_payment is highly correlated with offered_amount and should be ignored for analysis.

The rest of variables might be useful features for the model and they should be kept for further analysis:

  • apr, offered_amount, requested_amount, income are numerical varibles. Their distributions are highly right skewed. requested_amount and income have missing values.
  • traffic_source is listed as numeric variable here. However, based on the description of this variable: ID of the source through which lead was acquired, it should be a categorical variable.
  • term_length and term_unit can be combined into one varible using the same loan term unit.
  • credit_rating, loan_purpose, state are categorical variables and have missing values. Some categories for these variables only have a few observations, so those categories can be combined into one category and name'other'.
  • lender_id has 20 distinct values. They should be included as a categorical variable.
  • is_mobile has a large proportion of missing values, it's not a reliable feature for building the model. So it should be dropped for the modeling.
  • is_funded is the dependent variable that we want to predict. However, the class is highly imbalanced. Oversampling or downsampling is necessary before building the model.

In [6]:

for i in range(len(df)):
    if df['term_unit'][i] == 'month':
        df['term_length'][i] = df['term_length'][i]*30
    elif df['term_unit'][i] == 'year':
        df['term_length'][i] = df['term_length'][i]*365

III. Machine learning model¶

In this part, I will try five machine learning models: logistic regression, K nearest neighbors, SVC, decision tree and random forest. Before training the model,

  1. Check class imbalance and correlation coefficients
  2. If the class is highly imbalanced, oversampling techniques such as SMOTE will be used to balance the two classes.
  3. Data preprocessing: label encoding the dependent variable 'is_funded' and one-hot encoding for all the categorical variables.
  4. Try the above listed five machine learning models.
  5. Considering the possible imbalanced class, confusion matrix and roc-auc score need to be used for evaluation metrics.

In [36]:
def tsne_plot(x1, y1, name="graph.png"):
    tsne = TSNE(n_components=2, perplexity=100, random_state=0)
    X_t = tsne.fit_transform(x1)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    plt.scatter(X_t[np.where(y1 == 0), 0], X_t[np.where(y1 == 0), 1], marker='o', color='g', linewidth='1', alpha=0.8, label='Non funded')
    plt.scatter(X_t[np.where(y1 == 1), 0], X_t[np.where(y1 == 1), 1], marker='o', color='r', linewidth='1', alpha=0.8, label='Funded')

    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title("t-sne")
    plt.savefig(name)
    plt.show()

import itertools

# Create a confusion matrix
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    print(cm)

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=14)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

In this part, autoencoder will be used to decrease false negative rate and further improve model's performance.

V. Conclusion¶

In this data challenge, I built machine learning models to predict whether a user will accept the loan offer or not based on their click information. The main challenges for this dataset are:

  1. Highly imbalanced data set.
  2. Very high false negative rate using traditional machine learning models.

If the related marketing team is interesting in finding users who tend not to accept loan offers, simple logistic regression is good enough. However, if they care more about finding users who is very likely loan offers, SVM classifier with autoencoder representations can give reasonably accurate predictions.

Futher model refinement can be:

  1. There are some room to further improve random forest model's performance. Fine tuning hyperparameters for random forests is worthwhile trying to see whether the false negative rate can be decreased.
  2. Fine tuning hyperparameters and autoencoding part for SVM classifiers.
